# Answers:
# 1. All the values change very fast because, since we're dealing with quadratic drag, low values of velocity are small, but as the velocities increase, the force of drag blows up. This causes the positions to very quickly change. When looking back at the vertical position graph from the linear drag sim, we can see that it begins to deform away from the parabolic shape of motion in a vacuum, and more towards a line. Thus, I infer that drag causes the height graph to deform away from the parabolic shape and towards a linear shape (I don't really have a better explanation).
# 2. So much energy is lost due to heat because the force of drag is much stronger (for greater velocities, that is), and if the force is stronger, the drag does more work, meaning more energy is lost.
# 3. We use quadratic drag to model realistic projectile motion because in the real world, the force of drag from the air is usually always proportional to v^2.

